-161854"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gcrim"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001003-20180326-161854"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001003-20180326-161854"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">ST</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">3 men charged for hurting, verbal abuse against SCDF paramedics</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>SINGAPORE - Three men were charged on Tuesday (Mar 27) in separate cases of hurting and verbal abuse against paramedics from the Singapore Civil Defence Force (SCDF).</Para><Para>Singaporean Hamza Bin Mohamed Ibrahim, 50, was charged on two counts. He allegedly used criminal force and abusive language on paramedic Mohammad Ika Khairuz'zaman bin Mohammad Shah on Dec 18 last year at Fragrance Hotel in Wishart Road.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>He allegedly pushed the paramedic on his chest once, uttered words including a Malay vulgarity several times, and also told him "I can kill you".</Para><Para>He is out on a bail of $5,000 and is due to appear in court again on April 3.</Para><Para>Indonesian Adi Wijaya, 31, was charged on one count of using criminal force on a public servant. Wijaya is accused of kicking paramedic Ridzwan bin Rahmad once on his right thigh at a taxi stand in Clarke Quay on Sept 30 last year.</Para><Para>He is out on a bail of $3,000 and will return to court on April 3.</Para><Para>For using criminal force on a public servant, both men face up to four years in jail or a fine, or both.</Para><Para>Another Singaporean Lee Boon Chong, 47, was charged on one count of voluntarily causing hurt to a public servant. He is accused of hitting SCDF paramedic Whitney Luo Lilian in the neck.</Para><Para>He is now in remand at the Institute of Mental Health (IMH) and will be back in court on April 10. He faces up to a maximum of seven years in jail, a fine, caning, or a combination of the three penalties.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Jan Lee </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

